Introduction

The launch of the first rotation of parachain slot auctions on Kusama marked a major milestone in the development of the project and in achieving a scalable and decentralized future. It is exciting to see how many professional teams, many received funding from the Web3 Grants Program (CHECK), were ready to launch and competed for one of the five ever available parachain slots. This post gives some background information on the candle auction, the crowdloan mechanism, crunches some data (nothing too complicated though) and provides an outlook on potential developments in the auction dynamic. In addition to the chain data, this post incorporates results from an anonymous survey that was conducted prior to the auctions (end of March / early April) with fifteen parachain teams (footnote: Note that the responses of the teams do serve as clear prediction for the future as strategies and situations are likely to change).

The responses in the survey indicated that many teams made themselves ready for the long awaited start of the parachain auctions on Kusama. 10 out of 15 teams indicated that they are aiming to enter the race for the first available slots on Kusama. Most of the teams, in fact 80%, indicated that they plan to be eventually live on both Kusama and Polkadot (with 13.3% only on Kusama and 6.7% only on Polkadot). The survey also shows that the auctions have a very high priority for the teams where they indicated with an average of 6.5 (on a 7-point scale) that they extensively thought about the parachain auctions and strategies to acquire them.

The Candle Auction: A refresher

Before proceeding with the analysis of the individual auctions, it is a good idea to reiterate on the the auction mechanism. The candle auction is an old auction format from around the 16th century where bidding was allowed until a literal candle went out (see Blogpost). The uncertainty about the actual ending time of the auction was used to reduce auction sniping, which was already back then known to be an issue. This phenomenon describes the situation that bidders hold back until the last possible moment to squeeze their bid in to not give other participants the chance to react. Many of us probably made similar experiences in the past with online auction formats such as eBay.

The candle auction format was long neglected and hasnt seen much implementation. However, it has proven beneficial properties when combining it with the blockchain (link Samuels paper) both for avoiding sniping and XY. It is therefore utilized to sell the parachain slots on Polkadot and Kusama. In contrast to the ancient candle auction, the end is determined retrospectively. That means, the auction always has a fixed length and only after it ended, a verified random function (VRF-LINK) calculates the block that marks the end of the auction. We can mark four important checkpoints to describe the temporal procedure of a candle auction, described in block heights. The following graph illustrates the process.

1 |- - - - - (Starting Period)- - - - - - - - - - - - 2 - -(Candle Phase) - - - - - 3 - - - (Candle Phase)- - - - - - - - 4 <- having a nice graphic here. The dots could be blocks and the numbers could be bigger, specially colored blocks. Names of the phases could span over the respective areas. 1 = Start Auction 2 = Start Candle Phase 3 = Termination Block 4 = End Auction

The start and end block of the auction determine the fixed length of each auction and give participants certainty about the overall framework of the auction. The first phase of the auction, lasting exactly 27000 blocks (around 45 hours), serves as grace period where teams and users have time to get an overview of the situation, gather information and set up their bidding/contributing strategies. During this phase, the auction cannot end even though bidding is already enabled. After that, the candle phase (or ending phase) starts and marks the real beginning of the auction. Here, figuratively, the candle is lit and this phase lasts for 72000 blocks (around 5 days). During this phase, the auction could end at any given block with equal probability (i.e., the candle phase has a uniform termination profile) (footnote: More precisely: To reduce storage requirements, only every 20th block can be sampled and be selected as the termination block). Bidding is allowed until the end of the auction. After the official ending block, a Verified Random Function (VRF LINK) draws the block (termination block) that decides the winners of the auction by implementing the respective winning bids contained in that block. Later (winning)bids are discarded and, in the case of crowdloans, contributions remain locked for the whole duration of the slot. Thereby, the candle mechanism induces incentives to bid as early as possible (or at least shortly before the beginning of the candle phase) and thereby reduce sniping.

Crowdloan Mechanism

Crowdloans are a novel way for projects to raise funds to obtain the right to benefit from the shared security that the relay chain offers as a parachain. In contrast to other funding methods commonly applied on Ethereum, this process is trustless for users, who can be certain that they receive back the funds at a predefined date. Economically, the costs of their contribution is the opportunity costs they endure (e.g., the loss of staking rewards or a forgone return from using the funds differently). In essence, crowdloans are a simple module that is programmed to participate in an auction (or consecutive auctions) with a predefined and simple bidding strategy. The crowdloan can only bid for a single predefined period of time (in the recent case all crowdloans bid for the enteriety of the slot) and the bid automatically increases exactly by the amount that is contributed each block (footnote: To decrease the storage requirements, those bids are actually only cast on-chain once the candle period starts). If the crowdloan successfully won an auction, funds are automatically locked for the period of time and then be paid back to the accounts that contributed. If the crowdloan could not secure a slot, funds can be retrieved after the expiration of the crowdloan (which generally is only set for the duration of the auctions).

Auction Schedule

In total, the first rotation auctioned off five available parachain slots during June and July 2021. The first auction started at the June 15th and the last auction ended on the July 20th. Each auction lasted seven days with a two day starting period and five days of candle period. Auction Data

Let us dive into the data. As mentioned before, all bids were cast by crowdloans (with a few non-serious manual bids, which are discarded from the analysis because of their irrelevance). This was to be expected as 86.7% of projects predicted that theyd use crowdloans to raise funding in the survey, while 2 projects indicated that they will be bidding with their own funds. Either they changed their strategy or we can expect some individual bidders in the next sequence of auctions. Most projects said their project requires operation of at least 1 year, which is why all crowdloans were programmed to bid for the entirety of 8 leasing periods (13-20).

Overview

In total 17 unique crowdloans have registered to participate in the auctions and have received funding during the campaign from 18933 unique accounts. A total number of 1,302,636 KSM was contributed to the crowdloans. From that, 1,114,629 are locked in slots until May 13th, 2022 (200,633,234 USD), while the rest can be reclaimed by users, as their chosen crowdloans could not secure a parachain slot in this rotation. This means, that in 9.9% of all available tokens are currently locked in crowdloans. In addition, 47% are currently staked. Well have a closer look on each auction in the following.

Auction 1-3

From the very beginning, three strong teams crystallized and it was no surprise that theyd occupy the first three slots on Kusama. Karura (LINK), a DeFi focused project, took the lead from early on and surpassed all others teams by a large margin. Moonriver (LINK) which provides native Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) smart contracts on Kusama, started out lower than their competitors but was able to quickly surpass Shiden (which also focuses on providing smart contract functionalities) even before the candle phase started. Shiden (LINK), secured the third spot. In total, Karura raised 501,137.7 KSM (USD 90,204,779). Moonriver raised 205,935 KSM (37,068,302 USD) and Shiden 138,457.9 KSM (24,922,415 USD).

The following graph illustrates the dynamics of the crowdloan contributions of those three projects on a daily basis. The vertical lines correspond to the ending dates of the respective auctions. As all bids were made for the full slot period and cast by crowdloans, they correspond to the bids themselves. After a crowdloan successfully won an auction, contributions are no longer allowed and therefore the curve flattens out for the winners.

Auction 4

In contrast to auction 1-3, the fourth auction was, especially in the pre-candle phase, more dynamic. The main contestants were Bifrost, a project that aims to provide liquidity for staked tokens, and Khala (LINK), a confidential cloud computing service. The leading position switched periodically in this head-to-head race, as the following graph illustrates.

As mentioned before, the winning bid constantly changed before the candle phase started (indicated by the first vertical line). However, Khala could secure large contributions right in time with the start of the candle period and held the winning bid during all blocks. Bifrost was not able to catch up and therefore it was not surprising that Khala won the fourth parachain slot on Kusama.

Naturally, Bifrost was still in the race for the fifth and last slot and contributions increased after the end of the fourth auction (indicated by the second vertical line).

Auction 5

With a strong position from the fourth auction, Bifrost continued to compete for the last available slot. At first, it looked like it would be an easy win, as no other project came close to their contribution level. However, a strong competitor only started their crowdloan shortly before the start of the fourth auction and promised to be a strong competition to Bifrost. Basilisk, a Automated Market Maker (AMM) chain which provides liquidity bootstrapping functionality for any new cryptoasset, got traction and caught up quickly. The following graph illustrates the head-to-head race between the two teams.

While the pre-candle phase was easily lead by Bifrost, Basilisk managed to come very close to Bifrost with the important start of the candle auction and the winning bids even switched during that period. To get a better look on the details, we increase the resolution and switch to cumulative contributions on a block-level. The vertical line illustrates the beginning of the candle phase.

We can see that Basilisk had a few situations where they had the winning bid in the decisive candle phase. However, Bifrosts position was too strong and they lead 96.6% of blocks during the candle phase. Given that each block has the same chance of being pivotal for the outcome of the auction (footnote: Assuming that the percentage of samples correspond to the percentage of leading blocks), this heavily favored Bifrost to be the winner. At the end, Bifrost won the fifth auction and raised 136,817.8 KSM (24,627,203 USD) in the process.

The Impact of the Candle Mechanism

As explained in the introduction, the candle auction is composed of different stages that differ in their importance. While the general auction always lasts a fixed period of time, while the block that contains the actual winning bid is determined retrospectively. This could mean, that the highest bidder does not get the slot, because their winning bid is discarded and an earlier winning bid is considered. However, all funds that are contributed to a successful crowdloan, will be locked for the entirety of the respective leasing period. However, those bids did not contribute to a higher winning bid. In this rotation, this did not affect the outcome, but in future rounds it could be a decisive factor. The following table analyzes the contributions in more detail and separates them between the different important phases of the auction. Additionally, the table shows the respective time (in %) of when the termination block occured.

Future Developments (Redo this section)

We are living in exciting times where slot auctions finally arrived to the Kusama network. With the inclusion of Parachains, scalable and decentralized future. This marks a milestone in the development of the protocol and pushes it to the next level. The first five projects that are live on Kusama are Karura, Moonriver, Shiden, Khala and X. (Link to platforms). The first five projects extend the Kusama network with DeFi and smart-contract capabilities, confidential cloud computing and various ways to enjoy liquidity. Generally, the first rotation was quite successful and paves the way for the Polkadot auctions.

As we saw in the analysis, all projects funded themselves with crowdloans. With this mode of participation, the incentives diverge from those that underlie the assumptions of the auction participation. Generally, wed assume that bidders want to obtain the goods as cheap as possible. However, this might be different in the situation with crowdloans, because the projects do not (at least mostly) fund the slot by themselves. Even contrary to traditional auctions, the projects might even benefit from their higher bids, because it signals higher trustworthiness to the market and might increase the parachains valuation. Additionally, crowdloan contributors face trade-offs when contributing to projects. First, they are not doing so solely based on their preferences, because contributing to your favorite project which is predicted not to win, would waste opportunity costs (both of unbonding time, and the time the tokens are locked in crowdloans). Additionally, they might want to get in the project as early as possible. At some point, one could expect that the token price gets diluted if more funds go into a project, but this depends on how the parachain teams structure the rewards. If they mint more tokens to satisfy the increased demand in crowdloans, the token price should fall with higher supply. If, however, the token pool to be distributed is fixed and left over tokens remain in circulation, price should rather increase with more contributors (as network effect increases and the project has more outreach).

Generally, we can expect that future auctions are much more dynamic. On the one hand, we might see projects that are in the on-boarding phase (like all of them were in those sequence of auctions) where the use of crowdloans is natural and of great benefit. However, after being active, projects might be in the extension phase where they need to win other slots to sustain their operation. In this case, crowdloans might not be the best tool. Also, they might not go all for the full period but try to flick together their timetable based on where they can score the cheapest slots. In a survey prior to the auctions, around 30% of participating projects suggested that they will switch to some private form of bidding (i.e., non-crowdloans) in the future. Public bidding might be also including smart-contracts where funds are gathered in the platforms native token (maybe even from treasury). The former is similar to ICOs where project source funds from the crowd and offer platform benefits in exchange. However, this might change in the extension phase, where projects might utilize their own treasury or saving to extend the funds or fund with their own tokens. The reason being that it offers more flexibility (crowdloans are rather dumb and even overbid themselves and also it might get harder to provide platform rewards for new users. Additionally, with parachains, smart-contracts are possible and make it possible to source funds trustless while offering an interface for some more sophisticated bidding strategies. And it reduces the effort of conducting a crowdloan campaign. More flexible to jump into bidding for slots that are starting but might be cheaper. Overlapping explaining.
